<PB N="184" REF="185">to be dreaded, and has done the lea&s;t mi&s;chief. It may be truly &s;aid, that if licentiou&s;ne&s;s has de&s;troy|ed its thou&s;ands, de&s;poti&s;m has de&s;troyed its mil|lions. The former, having little power, and no &s;y&s;tem to &s;upport it, nece&s;&s;arily finds its own re|medy; and <HI>a people &s;oon get out of the tumult and anar|chy attending it.</HI> But a de&s;poti&s;m, wearing the form of government, and being armed with its force, is an evil not to be conquered without dreadful &s;trug|gles. It goes on from age to age, deba&s;ing the human faculties, levelling all di&s;tinctions, and preying on the rights and ble&s;&s;ings of Society.&mdash;It de&s;erves to be added, that in a &s;tate di&s;turbed by licentiou&s;ne&s;s, there is an animation which is fa|vourable to the human mind, and which puts it upon exerting its powers. But in a &s;tate habit|uated to a de&s;poti&s;m, all is &s;till and torpid, a dark and &s;avage tyranny &s;tifles every effort of ge|nius; and the mind lo&s;es all its &s;pirit and dignity.</P>
